<div id="stitle" style="display:none;">Notebook Entry</div>
<dl id="n05109g"> <dt class="nbunit"><a name="n05" href="#n05109g">N05 (VI.B.2)</a>:  <a href="../../ff/fnbs/n05all.htm#n05109g"> 109(g)</a></dt> <dd> <blockquote> I, a wretched small man / (if you like to say so) / have been revolving / &amp; possess a glowing sun / i.e. ineffably endowed / with pure urbanity</blockquote> <dd class="well"> <blockquote class="sources">The letter of Ardhelm to Eahfrid exhibits in turgid latin his naive irritation over the superiority of the Irish schools: &ldquo;<mark>I, a wretched small man, have revolved these things</mark> as I wrote them down and have been tortured with the anxious question: Why should Ireland &hellip; be exalted &hellip; as though here on this fertile turf of Britain teachers of Latin and Greek &hellip; cannot be found &hellip; and yet Britain (if you like to say so) &hellip; <mark>possesses a glowing sun</mark> and a lustrous moon, that is to say, Theodore, the archbishop of the island &hellip; and Adrian &hellip; <mark>ineffably endowed with pure ubanity</mark>.&rsquo; <small> Benedict Fitzpatrick, <a name="IIMB" href="../../ff/fdra/fdex.htm#IIMB"><cite title="source">Ireland and the Making of Britain</cite></a> (1922) 267-8</small></blockquote> </dd></dl>
